<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-08-19T12:35:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-08-19T12:35:00-05:00" n="400" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d400">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">891.00/1158: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Persia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Teheran</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-08-19T21:00:00+03:25"><hi rend="italic">August 19,
                                        1920—9 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received August 20—9:19
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>25. Persian situation is evidently much better and all excitement abated
                            owing to the success of Government troops sent against the rebels and
                            Bolsheviki.</p>
                        <p>Part of the British advisers who have been working for some time under
                            the provisions of the recent treaty are departing from Persia apparently
                            convinced that said treaty will never be accepted by the Persians.</p>
                        <p>There is nothing further to report.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>